Name: Brentwood Elementary School
Description:
Beginning July 28th, contactless Drive thru/walk up Grab-n-Go breakfast & lunch meal services will resume Monday through Friday each week FOR ALL BUSD STUDENTS & FAMILIES. A Hot Lunch & breakfast for next day will be provided. Additional Family Produce Boxes will be available two days per week with pickup/purchase of meals. On the Free/Reduced Meal Program? ALL MEALS FREE.
Distance Learning Student Meal Prices: $4.75 per student (lunch & breakfast combined)
Distance Learning Sibling/Adult Meals Prices: $7.00 per person (lunch & breakfast combined)
Have a younger sibling? Please ask about our Hungry Tummies program for free younger sibling meals.

Principals and staff members have food for students who were unable to pick up their lunches during the designated time.

Name: Alisal Community
Description:
As a reminder, we continue to feed all eligible children ages 1- 18 years old, regardless of the school they attend. And we continue providing meals without eligible children present with certain restrictions as follows:

1. Parents/ Guardians  who request up to four meals, without eligible children present, do not need to provide any information about the child(ren) theyre requesting meals for.
2. Parents/ Guardians who request five meals or more, without eligible children present, need to provide the names of school age students and their student ID one time only. If the ID number is unavailable, Parents/ Guardians can provide the names of the students, the name of the school they attend and the names of their teachers. This information only needs to be provided once.
3. Parents/Guardians who request five meals or more for eligible children, without children present, for children who are not attending school, please provide the age of each eligible child.
Please call the Nutrition Services department at (831) 753-5776 for additional information.

Name: Graves School

Name: Arroyo Seco Academy
Description:
Starting Monday, March 30th, two breakfasts and two lunches will be distributed together to
provide students with enough food for Mondays and Tuesdays.
 Starting Wednesday, April 1st, three breakfasts and three lunches will be distributed together
to provide enough food for Wednesdays, Thursdays, and Fridays.
 For students that live outside of our city limits, including Arroyo Seco residents, breakfasts
and lunches will be delivered at 9:45 a.m. to the normal bus stops on Mondays and Wednesdays
only. They will receive the same amount of meals as stated for students that pick up their meals
at the school sites above.
 Food that has not been picked up from the school sites will be delivered at 10:30 a.m.
Mondays and Wednesdays only at the current delivery locations.

Name: A.P. Giannini High School
Description:
Pop-up Pantry Thursdays, 9 a.m. - 1 p.m.
"Student Nutrition Services is committed to ensuring no child goes hungry and will provide free meals to all children in San Francisco while schools are closed. Free grab and go meals are available at the sites listed below. Each bag includes meals for multiple days: breakfast, lunch, supper, fresh fruit, vegetables, milk, and any necessary preparation guides. No identification or proof of school enrollment is required. Adults can now pick up meals for children without a child present. Shelf-stable meals will also be available. Families will not need to enter the school building for pick-up. Beginning Monday, March 30, we will be open two days per week but continue to provide five days worth of food. This new schedule reduces the number of days families need to leave home for pick-up but the amount of food each child will receive remains the same."

Name: Burlingame Intermediate
Description: In order to receive lunch, you must email lunch@burlingameschools.org or call 650-259-3814 to let us know that you wish to have a lunch for your child. When emailing or calling please leave the following information: Your name, students name(s), school site and any dietary restriction (i.e. vegetarian). You only need to make this call once to receive lunch; however, if there is a day you will not be needing a meal, please let us know. In addition, if meals are not picked-up two days in a row, we will consider you no longer want the meals. Monday's pickup will include food for Tuesday, and Wednesday's pickup will include food for Thursday and Friday. Please contact us by Tuesday, March 17, if you will need a lunch for your child.

Name: Davenport Resources Center
Description: Meals are free for ALL children ages 18 or below, regardless of income status, school enrollment, etc. Available for pick-up between 11:00 a.m. and 1:00 p.m. every school day at the Davenport Resources Services Center, 150 Church Street, Davenport. Children must be present to be served. Meals must be eaten off site. It will be hosting another emergency food distribution at DRSC on Wednesday, April 1st, from 2pm-4pm. Families are invited to come pick up produce and other staples they may need. Additionally, wed like to remind everyone that our pantry is remaining open, families can access our dry goods pantry Monday-Friday from 10am-6pm, we just ask that families call in advance as we are currently operating by appointment for pantry services. (831) 425-8115.

Name: Catholic Charities
Description: Catholic Charities is helping stabilize housing and ease the financial burdens of eligible San Franciscans, regardless of immigration status, through immediate, temporary financial assistance for housing costs such as rent, mortgage payments, security deposits, utilities, and/or HOA and other housing-related fees. Applications may be submitted online at Give2SFhousing.org or by calling Catholic Charities at 415-972-1283 or sending an email to Give2SFCOVID-19@CatholicCharitiesSF.org. The initial application period for these funds will be one-week.

Name: SFMTA
Description: The ETC will subsidize about two to three round trips by taxi per month for older adults (persons 65 and older) and people with disabilities. An older adult or persons with disabilities may apply for the ETC program by calling 311 and mentioning the program.

Name: Disaster Relief Assistance for Immigrants (DRAI)
Description:

Description:
Eligibility: Low-income Latino immigrants and their families who reside in Marin County AND who have lost their jobs or suffered a reduction in their income due to the COVID-19 pandemic and Shelter-in-Place order.
Apply online and you will be connected with a Canal Alliance staff member if they are able to match you with funds. May be more than a month after applying. Call if you need assistance in applying.

Name: Berkeley Relief Fund
Description:
Eligibility: Businesses or nonprofit organizations located within City of Berkeley with an active buisness license as of March 1 2020, Minimum 1 employee, Maximum 50 employees, Can demonstrate at least a 25% reduction in revenues due to COVID-19.
The City of Berkeley is making grants of up to $10,000 available to Berkeley-based small businesses and nonprofits to enable continuity through and beyond the COVID-19 pandemic. To apply complete the on-line application form. Funds must be used to cover payroll, rent, or working capital for the business to cover operational expenses.

Name: Berkeley Relief Fund
Description:
Eligibility: Organizations must be located in the City of Berkeley, must have been in operation for no less than one year, must have a majority of its arts activities in Berkeley for no less than one year. Other eligibility requirements listed on website.
The City of Berkeley is making grants of up to $25,000 available to Berkeley-based nonprofit arts organizations as early gap funding to help stabilize these organizations as they grapple with the initial financial impacts of the COVID-19 pandemic. Apply online.

Name: Berkeley Relief Fund
Description:
Eligibility: Berkeley residents or Berkeley Shelter Plus Care/Rapid Rehousing tenants who are at imminent risk of losing their permanent housing, grant must prevent eviction or support housing related financial assistance due to loss of income during the COVID-19 crisis, households must be at or below 80% of Area Median Income. Other eligibility requirements listed on website.
Berkeley's Housing Retention Program provides grant assistance to Berkeley residents at risk of eviction. Approved households can receive up to $5,000 as a one-time grant and an additional one-time grant of up to $10,000 during the COVID-19 emergency. The application period for housing retention grants has closed but you can be added to a wait list by calling number.

Name: Catholic Charities of San Francisco: Center for Immigration Legal & Support Services
Organization: Catholic Charities of San Francisco: Center for Immigration Legal & Support Services
Description: Provides consultations and legal advice for family-based petitions, adjustments of status, waivers, U&T Visas, removal proceedings, and other assistance. During COVID-19, fill out the appointment request form on website.

Name: Instituto Laboral de la Raza: Employment & Worker Protections Project
Organization: Instituto Laboral de la Raza: Employment & Worker Protections Project
Description: Provides labor rights education and advocacy. Offers a variety of legal services related to employment.

Name: Oasis Legal Services: Immigration Project
Description: Oasis Legal Services provides Affirmative Asylum, consultations to screen for immigration relief, residency, citizenship, and family petition services for LGBTQIA+ clients. Currently during COVID-19 intakes are free and Oasis is not charging for its services if clients cannot afford to pay; Oasis Legal Services requires clients to make an appointment.

Name: International Rescue Committee: San Jose Immigration Project
Organization: International Rescue Committee: San Jose Immigration Project
Description: IRC provides legal services towards residency and citizenship to immigrants in need of assistance in San Jose. The IRC is recognized by the Department of Justice to provide immigration legal services to any immigrant community in Northern California.
locations: CA 95128,San Jose,1210 South Bascom Avenue Suite 227

Name: International Rescue Committee: Sacramento Immigration Project
Organization: International Rescue Committee: Sacramento Immigration Project
Description: IRC provides legal services towards residency and citizenship to immigrants in need of assistance in Sacramento. The IRC is recognized by the Department of Justice to provide immigration legal services to any immigrant community in Northern California.

Name: Opening Doors: Immigration Project
Description: Opening Doors provides high-quality, affordable legal services to refugees, victims of crime, victims of human trafficking, and other low-income individuals in Sacramento and surrounding counties. Closed for in-person assistance but still available for telephone help.

Name: Sacramento Food Bank & Family Services Immigration Legal Services
Organization: Sacramento Food Bank & Family Services Immigration Legal Services
Description: Sacramento Food Bank & Family Services Immigration Legal Services offers low-cost immigration legal services to help eligible individuals navigate the complexities of obtaining lawful status in the United States. Consultations and other services are offered by appointment only. Closed for in-person assistance but still available for telephone help.

Name: The World Relief Sacramento Immigration Legal Services
Organization: The World Relief Sacramento Immigration Legal Services
Description: The Immigration Legal Services (ILS) program at World Relief Sacramento exists to partner with local churches and the wider community to provide low-cost, high-quality legal services to immigrants throughout the Sacramento area. Closed for in-person assistance but still available for telephone help.

Name: McGeorge School of Law Immigration Law Clinic
Organization: McGeorge School of Law Immigration Law Clinic
Description: Provides legal services to underserved non-citizen residents of Sacremento and surrounding counties below the poverty level. Closed for in-person assistance but still available for telephone help.

Name: Mil Mujeres: Immigration Program
Description: Mil Mujeres offers immigration legal services to low-income individuals in the Latino community with a specialization on immigration benefits for survivors of violent crimes in the United States. Closed for in-person assistance but still available for telephone help.

Name: Centro de Ayuda Legal para Immigrantes (CALI): Immigration Program
Organization: Centro de Ayuda Legal para Immigrantes (CALI): Immigration Program

Name: Catholic Charities of Santa Clara County  Immigration Legal Service
Organization: Catholic Charities of Santa Clara County  Immigration Legal Service

Name: Center for Employment Training (CET)- Immigration Services
Organization: Center for Employment Training (CET)- Immigration Services

Areas of assistance include: Adjustment of Status, Consular Processing, Employment authorization, Family-based petitions, CARA, Naturalization/Citizenship, Temporary Protected Status (TPS), U visas, Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) petitions, Deferred Action for Childhood Arrivals (DACA). Services are currently only available by phone.

Name: Mental Health Advocacy Project
